4/ Even though we exist in a web3 world, we still need to think about web1/2 risks.

Be safe out there and stay vigilant and sceptical!

3/ Even though there are certain protocols to help mitigate spoofing (SPF/DMARC/DKIM), it is generally easy to spoof a sender address and is not something to trust.

In this example, the sender domain should have been "@opensea.io" https://t.co/gx6R7QyE9n

2/ ALWAYS check the sender address - an incorrect domain is a positive indicator of a malicious actor. 

In saying that, it's very important to understand that the opposite is NOT TRUE - a correct sender address is NOT a negative indicator of a malicious actor. https://t.co/plVpKFS3cX

1/ Malicious actors are consistent in delivering these attacks via methods with a matter of urgency. 

This urgency catches people off guard and works in the exact same way that FOMO works - this urgency makes people think illogically and with less scepticism. https://t.co/1wYufoaZh8

Everyone please be aware that more phishing emails are being spotted in the wild. This is the same attack vector used in the hack last weekend.

There are a couple of things to learn from this particular example üßµ

@Shiggidy_Listic Think of it like this - you told your bank that a specific company has delegated authority to do anything with your Pokemon card collection in your vault. They can come and go as they please.

Revoking the contract is calling the bank and revoking that delegated authority.
